    "blogHandle": "art",
    "title": "Israeli Street Artists Worth Knowing",
    "excerpt": "",
    "contentHtml": "<p>Israeli street art reads differently from city to city. In Tel Aviv, walls turn fast and the conversation stays loose, political, funny, and restless. In Jerusalem, the work often lands with more symbolism and friction. Haifa brings its own mix of port-city texture, music, and counterculture. Taken together, the scene feels less like a single movement and more like a running argument across public space.</p>\n<p>A few names still anchor that conversation. Broken Fingaz Crew helped push Israeli street art beyond local fame with murals that feel loud, theatrical, and impossible to miss. Dede brought a softer kind of recognition, using repeated forms, animals, and layered symbols that people can spot from a distance and remember later. Know Hope turned spare black-and-white figures into a language of tension, loss, and solidarity. Solomon Souza made the shutters of Mahane Yehuda part of the city's nightly memory, painting faces that appear only after the market closes.</p>\n<p>What keeps the scene alive is not only the artists themselves, but the way the work stays exposed to weather, demolition, repainting, and argument. A wall in Florentin may last a season. A market shutter in Jerusalem can become part of a neighborhood ritual. Festivals help, but the stronger story is what happens between official invitations, late-night painting runs, and the next layer that shows up over the top.</p>\n<p>For collectors, that history matters. Prints and editions tied to street artists carry more weight when they still hold some of the urgency of the wall: a sharp line, a strange symbol, a joke that turns dark on second look. The best work does not just document graffiti culture. It keeps some of its speed.</p>",
